06383nam a22009375i 9789048544844DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485448447 a10.1515/97890485448442doi  a(DE-B1597)528058  a(OCoLC)1089126182  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aART0150802bisacsh04a809.93357900aGames and Game Playing in European Art and Literature, 16th-17th Centuries /ced. by Robin O'Bryan. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultures of Play ;v100tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. A Passion for Games -- tPart I: Chess and Luxury Playing Cards -- t1. "Mad Chess" with a Mad Dwarf Jester -- t2. Changing Hands. Jean Desmarets, Stefano della Bella, and the Jeux de Cartes -- tPart II: Gambling and Games of Chance -- t3. "A game played home". The Gendered Stakes of Gambling in Shakespeare's Plays -- t4. "Now if the devil have bones,/ These dice are made of his". Dice Games on the English Stage in the Seventeenth Century -- t5. The World Upside Down. Giuseppe Maria Mitelli's Games and the Performance of Identity in the Early Modern World -- tPart III: Outdoor and Sportive Games -- t6. "To catch the fellow, and come back again". Games of Prisoner's Base in Early Modern English Drama -- t7. Against Opposition (at Home). Middleton and Rowley's The World Tossed at Tennis as Tennis -- tPart IV: Games on Display -- t8. Ordering the World. Games in the Architectural Iconography of Stirling Castle, Scotland -- t9. The Games of Philipp Hainhofer. Ludic Appreciation and Use in Early Modern Art Cabinets -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of essays examines the vogue for games and game playing as expressed in art, architecture, and literature in sixteenth- and seventeenth-century Europe. Moving beyond previous scholarship on game theory, game monographs, and period and regional studies on games, this volume analyzes a range of artistic and literary works produced in England, Scotland, Italy, France, and Germany, which used the game topos to illuminate special themes. In essays dealing with chess, playing cards, dice, gambling, and board and children's games, scholars show how games not only functioned as recreational pastimes, but were also used for demonstrations of wit and skill, courtship rituals, didactic and moralistic instruction, commercial enterprises, and displays of status. Offering new iconographical and literary interpretations, these studies reveal how game play became a metaphor for broader cultural issues related to gender, age, and class differences, social order, politics and religion, and ethical and sexual behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aCultural Studies. 4aGame Studies. 4aHistory. 4aLate Middle Ages & Renaissance. 4aLiterary History and Criticism. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aCards.  aChess.  aDice.  aEarly Modern social history.  aGame Play.1 aChovanec, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuidicini, Giovanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrold, Megan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaethler, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLebens, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Bryan, Robin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aO'Bryan, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPackard, Bethany, econtributor.4